      <h1>Using Bibliographic Search</h1>
      <?CHUNK filename="help/contact-us.chnk" optional="1"?>
      <p>Bibliographic search lets you look for words that occur in author or title fields. (Fig. 1)<br/></p>
      <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1" align="center">
        <tr >
          <td>
            <img border="1" src="/digital-collections-style-guide/static/text/help/bib-query-form.png" alt="bibliographic form"/>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <span class="caption"><strong>Fig. 1:</strong> The bibliographic search query form.</span>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p><br/> To use the bibliographic form ...
                  </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Enter a term or phrase in the text box. Multiple words will be treated as a literal string,
                        not separately in an "any word" or "all words" sense. Use
                        an asterisk with a word stem to find variations on the word (e.g., searching for jo* will
                        match johnson, jones, etc.). All other punctuation will be ignored. See <?STATIC_LINK page="help/search-tips" title="Searching Tips" class="doclink" display="inline"?>.
                        <br/><br/></li>
        <li>Use the pulldown "Search in" menu to select an area of the text to search
                        within. "Citation" is all the metadata describing the item.<br/><br/></li>
        <li>Click the "search" button to submit the query.</li>
      </ol>
